   <abstract>James K. Polk's personal copy of Thomas Bradford's 1835 atlas. In addition to states, continents, and countries, the atlas contains population charts, depictions of animals, height of mountains and monuments, astronomical charts, drawings of various modes of transportation and dwellings, and various other statistics and lists.</abstract>
   <abstract>Thomas Gamaliel Bradford was a cartographer born in Boston, Massachusetts in 1802. He worked for the American Encyclopedia for a time, before revising Adrian Balbi's Atlas Designed to Illustrate the Abridgement of Universal Geography, Modern &amp; Ancient. He went on to publish A Comprehensive Atlas: Geographical, Historical &amp; Commercial in 1835.</abstract>
